'\" t
.TH "ReterminateVT" "7" "" "reterminatevt"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
reterminatevt - User Mode VT Replacement Terminals
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
ReterminateVT provides consoles on Linux systems that do not provide
the legacy VTs, to instead present the consoles with user mode instead.
.PP
ReterminateVT consists of three main components, for three different
cases where a terminal is needed:
.IP \[bu]
vTTY:
.RS 12
.BR vtty (7)
is intended for minimal systems that do not have a display manager, or
for failure conditions. (For example, a display-manager.service can set
\fBOnFailure\fR to \fBvtty-frontend@seat0.service\fR). Semi-headless
servers that would otherwise have the default
.B getty@.service
enabled, can have
.B vtty-frontend@seat0.service
or
.B vtty-seatmanager.service
enabled instead.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
UvTTY:
.RS 12
.BR uvtty (8)
is similar to vtty, however it is intended to be selected as a wayland
session from a display manager, for users who desire to only log in to
a fullscreen terminal, or test and develop display servers with
.B uvtty-launch
without starting a vtty over the display manager.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
recinit:
.RS 12
.BR recinit (8)
is for emergency fallback shells, either to start when an
initrd fails to mount the filesystem, or can be used to replace
.B init=/bin/bash
with
.B init=/sbin/recinit
for instance.
.RE
.SH See Also:
.BR vtty (7),
.BR uvtty (7),
.BR recinit (8),
.BR vtty-launch (1),
.BR uvtty-launch (1),
.BR vtty-seatmanager (8),
.BR seat-vtty (7)
